SIMPLE: spouse
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Spouse
<hw>Spouse</hw> <pr>(spouz)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>espous</ets>, <ets>espos</ets>, fem. <ets>espouse</ets>, F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧poux</ets>, <ets>⟦eacute⟧pouse</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>sponsus</ets>, <ets>sponsa</ets>, prop. p. p. of
<ets>spondere</ets>, <ets>sponsum</ets>, to promise solemnly, to engage
one's self. Cf. <er>Despond</er>, <er>Espouse</er>, <er>Respond</er>,
<er>Sponsor</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A man or woman engaged or
joined in wedlock; a married person, husband or wife.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At last such grace I found, and means I wrought,⟦br⟧
That I that lady to my <qex>spouse</qex> had won.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A married man, in distinction from a
<contr>spousess</contr> or <contr>married woman</contr>; a bridegroom or
husband.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At which marriage was [were] no persons present but the
<qex>spouse</qex>, the spousess, the Duchess of Bedford her mother, the
priest, two gentlewomen, and a young man.</q>
<rj><qau>Fabyan.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spouse</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Spouse
<hw>Spouse</hw> <pr>(spouz)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[See
<er>Espouse</er>, and <er>Spouse</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>To wed;
to espouse.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This markis hath her <qex>spoused</qex> with a ring.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Though <qex>spoused</qex>, yet wanting wedlock's solemnize.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She was found again, and <qex>spoused</qex> to Marinell.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spouse-breach</ent>⟦br⟧
